text: M25: When you want to relive a time in Magic when creatures sucked...
Much nostalgia
At least it is an old card without a modern reprint. I’m expecting mostly Theros and newer shit uncommons and commons that show just how many fucks this set doesn’t give.
The salt online is real
“As a store owner I won’t even sell this to my customers”

It’s not even the dollar value that irritates me. There has to be an EV cap. Maybe it could be higher or distributed better but whatever. I’m mostly annoyed by how flat out lazy the vast majority of their choices have been.
It’s the most low-effort feeling reprint set I’ve seen
What do you feel is missing?
Cards that haven’t already been reprinted a fuck ton of times would be a start
Zero people wanted a 7th Akroma. This is the 18th Armageddon in paper. Not even Doran players wanted another Tree.
More Stangg-type reprints would have been fine
If it’s gonna be a set filled with valueless stuff at least make it valueless stuff someone might want or we haven’t seen
My reprint rant ire will forever be directed at Niv Mizzet as the Guildpact representative
Vs literally every other choice
Niv-Mizzet was an awful choice.
Most of which have never had a reprint
There are many awful choices...rare slots+ in a masters set should not favor nostalgia over a needed reprint.
Except the claims to be favoring nostalgia seem spurious at best
You want to fill the uncommon and common slots with that dreck, go ahead. Those have no meaning to newer players, anyhow.
I started in 2015, so Stangg, Ghost Ship, etc. gets some folk's rocks off, but does shit all for me and many others.
BTW, you want AN akroma at Mythic...whatever, but both?
Conflux? Please...
I'm back on Imperial Recruiter at Mythic rant stage as well...
Mystic Snake at Rare?
(sigh)

Because when I think of Innistrad I think of Tree of Redemption and Triskadekaphobia. 

Obviously that argument isn’t the greatest for every card as you can’t have the most obvious cards from every set... but some choices like those are baffling.

My honest opinion at this point is not only are they being careful about printing as little value as possible but they’re also making sure to let future cards have room to spike. By reprinting Niv who already has reprints and no value they get to keep Teysa or something on the sidelines so if it spikes down the road for whatever reason it can then get treated as a marquee reprint.
Ruric Thar?
Hell's Caretaker?
It’s all safe lazy choices
BSZ? Bident? These are the most representative cards of those sets?
Ruric Thar is hot garbage for value, but at least he is playable in limited unlike Triskadekaphobia
Agree on USZ and Bident.
If you look at this as a time capsule, since the focus is nostalgia and history, is this what you envision represents the last 25 years of Magic?
Mind you, at $10 a pack?
With so much land destruction I’m so shocked we can’t even live the dream of assembling Tron
That was a huge miss too
I kinda had my hopes up for this set as a course correction but they got worse

Nitpicking about cultivate isn’t much help. If they want to promote multiple colors in draft that’s a better pick than forest-searchers. Cultivate is fine. IMO Kodamas Reach might have been better but it’s fine. The commons and uncommons are largely fine. We can correctly be critical of choices like Niv and Tree of Redemption. Putting together a draft set that uses at least one card from every single set is not easy and while they could have done better, they also got some things way right, like Port at rare, filters, and Azusa. I don’t think cultivate is the hill to fight and die on

Anyone know why specifically Magic cards were made to refer to themselves in the third person?
"When Festering Goblin dies" as opposed to "When this creature dies"

I imagine it must have to do with damage spells. "Deal 3 damage to target creature or player" on Lightning Bolt probably makes it sound like *you* deal the damage, as opposed to the spell, which would open the door for pedants to say you can lightning bolt a pro-red creature.
